    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#boardman-hayes1973"/>, p. 85, n. <citedRange>2099</citedRange> (ph., dr.)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>002300</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <w lemma="ἱαρός"><supplied reason="lost">h</supplied>ιαρὰ</w> τᾶς
                    <w lemma="θεά">θεο͂</w>  <orig><unclear>εν</unclear></orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Consacré(e) à la déesse <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Dedicated to the goddess <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Consacrata/i alla dea <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The goddess is probably Demeter. The form <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἱαρά</foreign>, if a feminine singular, would not apply to a krater, 
                    thus it might rather be a neuter plural, applying to several objects. The two last preserved letters do no longer make sense for us.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
